{
  "doc_id": "36809",
  "text": "Jacob et al. [CITATION_1] highlighted the effects of the complement cascade during SAE in LPS-treated mice. Genetically modified mice that overexpressed CR1-related y (Crry-tg), a potent complement inhibitor, had an attenuated inflammatory response, with less apoptosis and cerebral edema, after LPS infusion. In addition, inhibition of complement factor C5a in a CLP model was associated with improved BBB function. [CITATION_2] Cerebral blood flow: Brain ischemia has been described in the autopsy findings of patients following death from septic shock, suggesting that there may be alterations in cerebral blood flow during SAE. [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] Hypotension and low cardiac output could be related to these findings. Because most available data have been obtained from similar autopsy studies, it is uncertain whether cerebral blood flow reduction is universally present in SAE or is only found in extremely ill patients who eventually die. A myocardial depression in septic patients could be linked to insufficient blood flow to the organs, including the brain. [CITATION_6] Earlier reports also suggest that blood flow may be reduced in the brains of septic patients. [CITATION_7] Pfister et al. evaluated cerebral blood flow using transcranial Doppler in a small series of patients. [CITATION_8] There was no association between SAE and altered brain perfusion that was reported in the middle cerebral artery. However, the autoregulation of blood flow was disturbed in patients with SAE, suggesting that the septic brain is more susceptible to variations in mean arterial pressure.",
